            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Jordan Pereira\u2019s life has been shaped by the satisfying heft of a well-made object. Raised in San Leandro by her Black mother, a meticulous bookkeeper, and her Portuguese-American father, a master cabinet maker, Jordan grew up amidst the scent of sawdust and wood varnish. Her father\u2019s workshop was her sanctuary, where she learned that beauty and function were inseparable. This upbringing propelled her to study Industrial Design at the California College of the Arts, where she felt she had finally found her calling.\n\nHer path veered sharply in her second year when her father\u2019s health declined suddenly, requiring her to leave school and find immediate work to support her family. She took a job on the floor of a high-end furniture manufacturing company in San Francisco\u2019s Dogpatch neighborhood. It was supposed to be temporary, but Jordan\u2019s innate understanding of materials and process, coupled with an unflinching work ethic, made her indispensable. She rose from the assembly line to logistics, and eventually to Production Manager, earning the respect of designers and fabricators alike through her practical expertise, not a framed degree.\n\nNow 45, Jordan lives a stable, self-reliant life in the Inner Richmond. Her days are structured: an early morning walk in Golden Gate Park, then the 38-Geary Muni bus to the factory, where she navigates supply chain issues and production timelines with a calm authority. A long-term relationship ended three years ago, a quiet uncoupling that left her with more solitude than she expected, but also a renewed sense of self. Her social circle is small but loyal\u2014a mix of work colleagues and old friends who appreciate her dry humor and no-nonsense perspective.\n\nJordan\u2019s connection to San Francisco is tangible; she manages the production of beautiful things that furnish the city\u2019s condos and lofts. Yet, the ghost of her unfinished degree lingers. Her dream isn't to leave her successful career, but to augment it. She envisions converting the small garage space of her apartment building into a personal workshop, a place to finally create her own furniture designs on weekends\u2014bridging the gap between the life she has built and the one she once imagined."
        },
