            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being ten, the smell of walnut dust sharp in the air. Her father\u2019s large hands guided hers as she fit the tail of a dovetail joint into its pin. When it slid together, perfectly flush without glue, a jolt of pure satisfaction shot through her. It was a perfect, honest union of strength and grace. In that quiet click of wood on wood, she learned her life\u2019s core philosophy: beautiful things work, and things that work are beautiful. This feeling became her standard.\n\n2.\nShe was nineteen, in the loud, chaotic studio at CCA. Her hands were caked in gray modeling clay as she sculpted a new kind of kitchen scale. For hours, the world fell away. There was only the rightness of the curve in her palm, the satisfying balance of the form. When she stepped back, she knew with absolute certainty that she had found her language. The feeling was pure, unburdened potential, a bright flame she still shields from the wind.\n\n3.\nThe Dogpatch factory, age twenty, was an assault. The shriek of the CNC machine vibrated in her bones, a universe away from her father\u2019s hushed workshop. Her first task: sanding chair legs, an endless, soul-numbing procession. Each abrasive swipe felt like a step away from her future. But by lunch, a stony resolve had settled in her gut. If she had to be here, she would be the best. It was the moment pride was forged from pragmatism, a foundation she built her entire career on.\n\n4.\nA week after he moved out, she stood in the living room, holding two coffee mugs. She was forty-two. She\u2019d made coffee for two out of sheer habit. The silence was absolute, punctuated only by the distant hum of the 38-Geary. Looking at the second mug, she felt not grief, but a profound quiet. This space, this life, was now entirely hers to furnish. The loneliness was real, but so was the sudden, unexpected feeling of a clean, uncluttered blueprint for one.\n\n5.\nOn her morning walk last spring, she stopped near the Dutch Windmill. A Monterey cypress, sculpted by decades of coastal wind, stood against the fog. Its trunk was a study in functional sculpture\u2014strong, weathered, yet impossibly graceful. An idea for a table leg, mimicking that exact curve, struck her with the force of a physical blow. It was a direct command from the nineteen-year-old girl with clay on her hands. The garage wasn't just a dream anymore; it was the next logical, necessary step."
